&gt; I found, upon looking into it, that Eclipse does have the /option/
&gt; of keeping the JUnit process/JVM running, so it can restart
&gt; individual test instances.
&gt;
&gt; Eclipse 3.0.1 gives me this informative error message:
&gt;   &quot;To rerun tests they must be launched under the debugger
&gt;    and &#39;Keep JUnit running&#39; must be set in the launch configuration&quot;
&gt;
&gt; So this only works with DEBUG runs.  And then only if you enable
&gt; it.  (And it can only be enabled if your JVM supports &quot;hot code
&gt; replacement.&quot;)  This is not the default behavior.
&gt;
&gt; (And *good luck* if you&#39;re using NetBeans, JBuilder or ant, and you
&gt; want process and instance preservation across runs!!!   ;-)
&gt;
&gt; From &quot;help&quot; documentation:
&gt;   &#39;A JUnit launch configuration has a &quot;keep alive&quot; option. If your
&gt; Java virtual machine supports &quot;hot code replacement&quot; you can fix the
&gt; code and rerun the test without restarting the full test run. To
&gt; enable this option select the Keep JUnit running after a test run
&gt; when debugging checkbox in the JUnit launch configuration.&#39;
&gt;
&gt; ...
&gt;
&gt; Otherwise, it launches a new process (new JVM, new test object
&gt; instances) on each JUnit run.
&gt;
&gt; To see this behavior, select &quot;Window -&gt; Preferences&quot;, &quot;Run/Debug -&gt;
&gt; Launching&quot; and uncheck the &quot;Remove terminated launches when a new
&gt; launch is created&quot; option.
&gt;
&gt; Then, in the &quot;Debug&quot; view (so you can see the list of processes, run
&gt; a few tests.  Each one gets its own process.
&gt;
&gt; Now it&#39;s true that when my &#39;suite()&#39; method builds tests from
&gt; standard TestCase classes with standard test methods, I can rerun
&gt; any test class or method with a right click, &quot;Run&quot;.  But each one
&gt; spawns a separate process.
